text: Hi Josh, hope you're well. hows it been going?
Hi Chris, a bit burnt out if I'm honest :persevere::grin:
Hope you're doing well.
oh no :disappointed: do you have your deadlines coming up soon ?
Yeah Friday at 3pm is the dead deadline :joy:
And I've been working nonstop since Thursday of last week, did an all nighter on Sunday to get them a draft for Monday :grin:
Then on Tuesday they added a scene that had been cut in week one back in, and then today an entirely new scene that wasn't even in the story boards to "tie it together" :joy:
On top of a generous amount of changes :joy:
oh gosh, thats so frustrating to deal with these edit changes
its probably not reassuring to know but that also happens on series productions

I'm just worried because I'm rushing now and I know for a fact that it's not my best work :persevere:
you feeling happy with your work?
that's frustrating too. Do you feel the sequences at least ' good enough ' ?

in general it works for the short tho, theres a charm to it not being perfectly smooth :slightly_smiling_face:
How do you do a week's worth of work in less 24 hours? :joy:
Haha just kidding, Is there anything major about it that screams bad student film? :grin:
hahaha, do you know the term 'triage' ?
its originally a french term for how to deal with medical emergencies
No? :joy:

but basically, doing triage means categorising your problems. Low - medium - high priority. Ignoring the low ones until everything else is done, giving a little bit of attention to the medium ones, and making sure the high priority have most of your attention
so it could be helpful to go over the film, and note which scenes are fine, which ones you'd like to improve, and which ones you need to improve
Yeah, I'm doing the bigger changes first so that if I run out of time it won't be the end of the world.
good job

the way the handle is currently makes it look like the handle is opening away from us, but the closeness of the shadow make it look like its coming towards us
